WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:03.154
SPEAKER_00: Cold mattered because rubber does not respond the same way in cold.

00:00:04.075 --> 00:00:07.799
SPEAKER_00: A seal that moves quickly when warm can respond more slowly when cold.

00:00:08.580 --> 00:00:11.544
SPEAKER_00: In this joint, timing was not a detail.

00:00:12.345 --> 00:00:14.467
SPEAKER_00: Timing was the safety margin.

00:00:15.288 --> 00:00:18.652
SPEAKER_00: If the seals failed, there was no graceful backup.

00:00:19.312 --> 00:00:26.780
SPEAKER_00: Hot gas could burn through the booster casing, reach surrounding structure, and turn a local leak into a vehicle failure.

00:00:27.082 --> 00:00:29.966
SPEAKER_00: The o-ring problem had been showing itself before Challenger.

00:00:30.025 --> 00:00:33.890
SPEAKER_00: Post-flight inspections found erosion on the primary seal.

00:00:34.652 --> 00:00:38.856
SPEAKER_00: In some cases, gas had blown past it and left evidence deeper in the joint.

00:00:39.857 --> 00:00:41.460
SPEAKER_00: Engineers documented the damage.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:42.701
SPEAKER_00: They measured it.

00:00:43.323 --> 00:00:44.084
SPEAKER_00: They reported it.

00:00:44.905 --> 00:00:47.368
SPEAKER_00: The dangerous part is what happened next.

00:00:47.719 --> 00:00:57.005
SPEAKER_00: Because the mission succeeded, because the vehicles came home, damage could be processed as evidence that the system had tolerated the condition.

00:00:58.048 --> 00:01:01.317
SPEAKER_00: A damaged component in a surviving system can be read two ways.

00:01:02.298 --> 00:01:03.703
SPEAKER_00: One reading says,

00:01:03.682 --> 00:01:09.271
SPEAKER_00: We were closer to failure than we should have been, so we stop and fix the condition before we repeat it.

00:01:10.093 --> 00:01:18.063
SPEAKER_00: The other says, the vehicle survived, the margin held, and the risk can be carried while improvement work continues.

00:01:19.025 --> 00:01:22.430
SPEAKER_00: The second reading became easier each time the shuttle flew and returned.

00:01:23.072 --> 00:01:28.560
SPEAKER_00: What had started as a serious anomaly gradually became part of the operating history.

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:30.522
SPEAKER_00: The O-ring warning did not disappear.

00:01:31.323 --> 00:01:31.805
SPEAKER_00: It moved.

00:01:32.605 --> 00:01:39.135
SPEAKER_00: That is how a warning can die inside a large organization, not through silence, through translation.

00:01:40.176 --> 00:01:42.760
SPEAKER_00: It starts when an engineer sees something wrong.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:44.882
SPEAKER_00: The data is specific.

00:01:45.483 --> 00:01:46.784
SPEAKER_00: The language is uncomfortable.

00:01:47.406 --> 00:01:47.867
SPEAKER_00: Erosion.

00:01:48.468 --> 00:01:48.927
SPEAKER_00: Blow by.

00:01:49.588 --> 00:01:50.751
SPEAKER_00: Heat effects.

00:01:50.730 --> 00:01:53.694
SPEAKER_00: a seal that did not behave the way the design assumed.

00:01:54.674 --> 00:01:56.495
SPEAKER_00: Precise evidence has force.

00:01:57.337 --> 00:01:59.498
SPEAKER_00: Then the evidence becomes a discussion item.

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:07.066
SPEAKER_00: It enters a meeting with dozens of other concerns, other anomalies, other systems, other deadlines.

00:02:07.887 --> 00:02:11.150
SPEAKER_00: The context broadens, and the urgency flattens.

00:02:11.811 --> 00:02:14.712
SPEAKER_00: From there, the discussion becomes a judgment call.

00:02:15.454 --> 00:02:17.616
SPEAKER_00: Does this affect the next flight?

00:02:17.596 --> 00:02:20.723
SPEAKER_00: The answer depends on the question the room decides to ask.

00:02:21.485 --> 00:02:24.673
SPEAKER_00: If the question is, can we prove this will cause a failure?

00:02:25.335 --> 00:02:26.538
SPEAKER_00: The answer is usually no.

00:02:27.419 --> 00:02:30.467
SPEAKER_00: Predicting a specific loss on a specific flight is hard.

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:34.217
SPEAKER_00: If the question is, can we prove this will not fail?

00:02:34.276 --> 00:02:36.001
SPEAKER_00: The answer is also no.

00:02:36.802 --> 00:02:39.890
SPEAKER_00: But the first question keeps the schedule alive.
